able piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Miles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Norman origin but uncertain derivation. Unlike most Norman names it is, as far as can be ascertained, not derived from any known Old French or Germanic name element. It may be a greatly altered pet form of   Michael  , which came to be associated with the Latin word <i>miles</i> ‘soldier’ because of the military attributes of the archangel Michael. However, the usual Latin form of the name in the Middle Ages was <i>Milo</i>. There is a common Slavic name element <i>mil</i> ‘grace, favour’, with which it may possibly have some connection. The name has been in regular use in England since the 16th century.  See also  Milo   and   Myles ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"'le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mareshall'","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, derived from a Norman French occupational term that originally denoted someone who looked after horses, ultimately from Germanic <i>marah</i> ‘horse’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’. By the time it became fixed as a surname it had the meaning ‘shoeing smith’ later it came to denote an official whose duties were to a large extent ceremonial. The surname is pronounced the same as the Latin name <i>Martial</i> (from Latin <i>Mars</i>, genitive <i>Martis</i>;  compare  Martin  ). This may have contributed something to its use as a given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Marshal","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, derived from a Norman French occupational term that originally denoted someone who looked after horses, ultimately from Germanic <i>marah</i> ‘horse’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’. By the time it became fixed as a surname it had the meaning ‘shoeing smith’ later it came to denote an official whose duties were to a large extent ceremonial. The surname is pronounced the same as the Latin name <i>Martial</i> (from Latin <i>Mars</i>, genitive <i>Martis</i>;  compare  Martin  ). This may have contributed something to its use as a given name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Miles 'le Mareshall' de Venoix was born about 1020, in Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France as the son of Ibert 'le Marshal' de Venoix. He married Lesceline before 1035, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1070, in Bavent, Calvados, Normandy, France, at the age of 51, and was buried in Le Tréport, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France."},"et":{"Abt 1020–1070":"umbes 1020–1070","1020–1070":"1020–1070","–Female":"Surnud","1035–1086":"1035–1086","1037–Male":"1037–Surnud","1049–1086":"1049–1086","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","before 1049":"enne 1049","before 1035":"enne 1035","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","Abt 1020":"umbes 1020","0995":"0995","1049":"1049","1037":"1037","1035":"1035","about 1035":"umbes 1035","about 1037":"umbes 1037","Venoix, Caen, Calvados, Normandie, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bavent, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Bavent, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Le Tréport Abbey, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Le Tréport, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Europe":"Europe","Venoix-near-Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bavent, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Bavent, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1020–1070":"noin 1020–1070","1020–1070":"1020–1070","–Female":"Kuollut","1035–1086":"1035–1086","1037–Male":"1037–Kuollut","1049–1086":"1049–1086","0995–Male":"0995–Kuollut","before 1049":"ennen vuotta 1049","before 1035":"ennen vuotta 1035","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1050":"1050"